<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910222-0028</DOCNO><DOCID>910222-0028.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- BellSouth Corp.:   Price on Proposed Purchase   Of Graphic Scanning Is Cut</HL><DATE>02/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3C</SO><CO>   BLS GSCC</CO><IN>TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)</IN><LP>   BellSouth Corp. said it and Graphic Scanning Corp. agreedto a lower purchase price for Graphic Scanning of $5.30 ashare, or about $172 million, after BellSouth completed areview of the proposed acquisition.   BellSouth, the Atlanta-based regional Bell telephonecompany, said the lower price reflects a negotiatedsettlement of certain purchase-price adjustments, includingtax considerations, contained in the original agreement.BellSouth had agreed earlier this year to acquirecash-strapped Graphic Scanning for $5.50 a share, or about$180 million.</LP><TEXT>   The two companies said the price will still be adjusted toreflect operations from Sept. 30 until the closing date aswell as proceeds from the sale of certain Graphic Scanningbusinesses. Graphic, based in Englewood, N.J., providescellular telephone service in Indiana and Wisconsin and haspaging and so-called wireless cable television properties inthe U.S. and the United Kingdom.   Graphic plans to sell manufacturing and informationservices operations as well as so-called wireless cable andFM-radio partnership interests to comply with antitrustrestrictions on BellSouth's business. Under the consentdecree that broke up the Bell System, BellSouth can'tmanufacture telephone equipment or provide informationservices or long-distance service.   The companies expect to complete the transaction, which issubject to various approvals, in mid-1991. Graphic Scanningwill become part of BellSouth Enterprises.</TEXT></DOC>